`crates/ctx-scan/tests/` is the black-box integration spec for the `ctx-scan` crate's two public entry points: the scan/summarize pipeline (`summarize`, `check_run`, `update_run`, `walk_dir`, `hash`) and the Claude Code Stop-hook (`cli::stop_hook`). Anything depending on `ctx-scan` should treat these tests as the executable contract for both surfaces.

Both files share the same tmpdir discipline: each test gets a uniquely named directory under the OS temp dir, manually `remove_dir_all`'d before (and usually after) rather than relying on shared harness teardown, so leftover state from a crashed run can leak into a later one. Both also depend on real prompt files existing under `../../prompts` relative to `CARGO_MANIFEST_DIR` when exercising the real `update_run` flow (`StdFs`/`StubAgent` in stop_hook.rs, and the equivalent real-fs tests in scan.rs) — moving or renaming those prompts breaks both files' tests simultaneously.

The two files test complementary halves of one invariant: `stop_hook` must never itself change tree freshness (staleness persists across a `stop_hook` call), while `update_run`'s incremental regeneration — which `stop_hook.rs` uses only to seed a fresh baseline — is exhaustively verified in `scan.rs`. A change to `check_run`'s fresh/stale semantics or to `MAX_TARGETS` gating affects both files' assertions and must be updated in lockstep.

`scan.rs` also carries the harness (`FakeFs`, `RecordingAgent`) used to test the pipeline hermetically in-memory, in addition to real-filesystem coverage; `stop_hook.rs` has no hermetic path and always exercises real files via `StdFs`.